The diagonal lines in the lateral heel area are orientated as one would expect in a manufacturer design, however I would want to check with the manufacturer (and/or SICAR) to see if this main design also comes with the diagonal lines, as seen. This design without the diagonal lines has been seen several times, whereas I do not recall experiencing this design with the diagonal lines. Also, other than the diagonal lines the correspondence of class characteristics is exceptional. Also, I would want to see if there are additional scene impressions that depict this outsole pattern again with or without the same diagonal lines? Furthermore, I would like to see additional scene photos for different footwear impressions which included parallel lines that could have created an artifact by overlapping. These diagonal lines do not penetrate the perimeter of the lateral heel lug, as would be expected during a random overlap, but overlapping is still a possibility. If this is an overlap, it is more likely a carefully constructed overlap, than a random one. Also to note, the splaying of dust as seen at the lateral heel area may be expected in the case of an overlap, but then again the entirety of the heel area displays a degree of splaying not seen in the ball/toe areas. The bottom line is; I want to say that there is an association of class characteristics, but I can not do that until I am satisfied that the parallel lines are an overlap, and not part of the manufacturers design.

I recognize/recall this exact case study from a previous package. My dilemma, at that time, was the diagonal lines within the bottom lateral corner of the questioned impression. I was unable to discern these lines as included class characteristics, or an overlap. Therefore, I had submitted ìinconclusiveî. However, due to my subsequent Black Box experience I have since encountered numerous more cases involving the EMS Day Hiker footwear, all of which do not possess the diagonal lines. Furthermore, I have since gained experience interpreting scanned gel lifts through the Black Box Study. I can now see that the matrix of the questioned impression differs from the diagonal lines, indicating an overlap. Hence, my conclusion in this case understandably differs from my previous conclusion.
